*--*  9/13/96  -  2:05:27 AM  *--*
polished till it gleamed with soft light.  The bristles were soft, and
looked like nothing I'd ever seen before.  I raised it to my head, and
my entire hand began to tingle.  Sur
prised, I dropped the brush onto the floor.

Tnai slapped her thighs, and laughed till tears ran down her face.
Through her giggles I made out the words "magic" , "Untangles", and
"useful to have friends who give you gifts".  Her laughter was
infectious, and soon I was giggling along with her
.  Somewhere in it all, she picked up the brush again and made a few
more passes over my head.  I lifted my hand to touch my hair.  It was
still dirty, but the tangles were gone.

        Tnai looked over at a large wooden tub on the floor.

        "We'll need more water than that," she said.  She opened a
pouch, removed a dried leaf and chewed it.  She was silent for a moment,
seeming to listen for something far off.  Then she smiled.  "There.
That's all set!"

Her hair swung forward to cover her face as she removed a lace scarf
from the top of the trunk and threw it open.  Colors gleamed softly from
the inside, shimmering and reflecting the light.  She began rummaging
through it all, carelessly pushing it
side in a jumble.  Finally, she pulled out a few things and closed the
trunk.  There was a knock at the door in the same pattern my brother had
used.  Tnai clapped her hands together and smiled as she opened the
door.  A scruffy aelfen mage stood the
re.  She pulled him inside and closed the door.

        "Taran! You`," she said.

        The mage looked a bit bewildered.  He shook his head as if to
clear it.

        "MMm, yes..." he mumbled.  "I got your message and started
coming in this direction, thinking how much I enjoy being here, and
there was a flash and... well, here I am!"
         Taran shook his head to clear it again, then glanced at me.  A
startled look crossed his face.

        "Tnai!" he exclaimed. "She's a bit young, isn't she?"

        Tnai shot him a look I didn't quite understand.  Then she looked
at me.

        "How old are you, Delight?" she asked.

        I shrugged.

        "Nine," I said. "Maybe ten."

        Tnai shook her head at Taran.

        "She's not, Taran" she said.  "But Davon would kill me.  You
know how he is about... well you know."

        A worried look crossed the little aelf's face.

        "Davon..." he muttered.  "Davon.. I think I'll be going now..."

        He turned toward the door.  Tnai grabbed him by the elbow.

        "Taran!"

        He stopped.

        "Would you magic me some water before you go?  Please?"

        Taran looked at her with a long-suffering expression.  Tnai
smiled at him tilting her head to one side.  He sighed.

        "I can never say no to you, Tnai," he said.

The little mage chanted a few lines, then gestured.  The air crackled
and a small cloud formed over the tub.  He gestured again and the little
cloud darkened ominously.  Lightning arced from it and it began to rain
into the tub.  After a few minutes
he incanted another phrase and gestured.  A puff of wind blew the cloud
away.  Tnai clapped her hands and giggled behind him.  He motioned for
her to be quiet.  Opening a pouch by his side, he withdrew an obsidian
rod, dipped it into the water and st
irred.  Little wisps of steam rose off its surface.  Taran carefully
dried the rod on his tunic and placed it back in the pouch.

        Tnai threw her arms around his neck and kissed him on the cheek.


        "You're wonderful!" she exclaimed.  The tips of his ears pinked.

        "Well," Taran started.  Then he cocked his head to none side as
if listening intently.
        "oh my... dear, dear...I'd better be on my way, dear," he said.
The door closed behind him and I heard him mutter a muffled phrase or
two.  A flash of light showed briefly under the door, and then silence.
Tnai shook her head, grinning.

        "He's sweet," she said. "He never can get his spells to work
properly, though. Wonder where he's bumbled into now."

        She motioned to the tub.

"Now, off with that grimy thing and into the tub with you," she ordered.
 I stared at the tub.  Tnai shook a handful of powdered grains out of a
crystal flask like the one my brother had scavenged from the bin in the
bazaar, and dropped them into th
e tub.  The water foamed and the scent of roses filled the air.  She
turned to me and raised one eyebrow.

        "Are you going to take it off, or shall I help you?"

It was a tone of voice there was no arguing with.  I quickly shucked off
the filthy tunic, and kicked my worn sandals off of my feet.  The
steaming water warmed me right through to my insides.  Tnai rubbed some
of the rose grains onto a cloth, dippe
d in the water and handed it to me.

"Start with your face,"she said.  I scrubbed at my face with the cloth,
then worked my way down my neck and shoulders.  The clear water turned
gray, then almost black.  Tnai ducked my head under water, and giggled.
She poured rose grains directly o
my hair and rubbed it in, then ducked me again and again, until I was
spluttering.

        Tnai looked me over critically, then nodded.

        "All right," she said.  The towel she handed me was soft and
fluffy and warm.  Glancing at the tub, she said, "Davon can drag that
out and empty it when he gets here!"
She motioned to the brush that still lay on the bed.  I picked it up,
and began brushing my hair with it.  This time the tingle was familiar,
and by the time I had finished, my hair was dry and tangle free.

        Tnai picked up the clothes she had laid out on the bed.  She
shook it out, and held a pale blue tunic up to her body.

        "I outgrew this last year," she said.  I looked longingly at the
darker blue sufa flowers embroidered at the neck and hem.

        "I think it will fit you. Here!"

She tossed it across the bed to me, then dropped to her knees and began
rummaging around under the bed.  I could hear her muffled muttering as
she tossed aside a black sandal, a green moccasin and a lavender pair of
boots.  Then there was a muffled
exclamation of triumph and she backed out from under the bed holding a
pair of cobalt blue boots of soft suede.  She waved them at me, her
green eyes twinkling.

        "Knew these were under here somewhere,"she said.  "What, haven't
you got that on yet?"

Tnai scooped the tunic up and slipped it over my head.  It smelled sweet
and a little musty at the same time.  I let the towel fall and struggled
to get my arms into the sleeves.  Pulling me to my feet, Tnai tugged the
soft fabric down over my hips.
  My head popped through the neck, and Tnai slipped her hands inside the
collar pulling my hair out of it.
She picked up the brush from where i had left it on the whiter fur
cover, and passed it over my hair.  The tingle was more than familiar
now, it was comforting, and I found myself filled with the warmest
feelings toward Tnai.  I grinned at her happil
y.   Tnai's face brightened.

        "There now," she said.  "It's the first I've seen you smile"

        She cocked her head to one side, and studied my face intently.

        "I may have been wrong about you never being a beauty," she
said.  "Did Davon leave that ribbon?"

I glanced around the room, and spotted it lying on a small table by the
door.  It shimmered in the soft candle glow as Tnai grabbed it.  Halfway
across the room she stopped short in surprise, looking down at the
ribbon in her hand.  She shook her he
ad as if something were stuck inside that wouldn't come loose.

        "Delight," she said slowly.  "What color was this ribbon?"

        A frown creased my forehead.  It was an odd question to ask when
she held the ribbon in her hand.

        "Red, Tnai,' I said.  "Almost the color of Davon's shirt."

A slow smile spread across her face.  She held the ribbon up for me to
see.  In the candlelight, it shimmered a deep rich green.  The color was
a perfect match for the lace that edged her gown, and the underclothes
that showed through it.  I felt my
 head shaking the same way that Tnai's had a moment ago.

        "Delight," she said.  Then again,"Delight..."

        She giggled.

        "Here, take the ribbon."

        I reached out and took it from her hand, watching it carefully.
As I touched it, my fingers tingled almost imperceptibly.  The
candlelight flickered, and I held a deep cobalt blue ribbon in my hand.
Tnai burst into giggles.

        "It's enchanted, Delight" she laughed.  "It changes to match the
person,  or at least their clothes!  You'll never need another ribbon!"

I stared down at the ribbon in my hand, remembering that Sharon the
weaver had smiled when Davon made his choice.  I held it against the
tunic I wore.  It was exactly the blue of the embroidered sufa flowers
on the hem.  I looked up and met Tnai's a
mused stare.  Her eyes danced.  Quickly, she made one more pass over my
hair with the brush, then expertly wove the ribbon through it.

        "Now, go look in the mirror," she exclaimed.

I gasped at what I saw.  Tnai had been generous in saying that I might
be a beauty, but the face that looked back at me was a far cry from the
pinched dirty little face I had seen a short while ago.  My cheeks were
not quite as hollow, and my eyes g
lowed.  The biggest change, though, was the hair.  Free of mats and
dirt, it glowed a deep rich brown in the candlelight, and billowed and
tumbled over my shoulders in rippling waves.  Behind me, I heard the
patterned knock at Tnai's door, and Davon'
voice calling for her to open.  I couldn't pull my eyes away from my
reflection, even when his face appeared behind mine in the mirror.  His
eyes widened and he shook his head.

        "Ah, Delight," he said, smiling a bit.  "I fear my
responsibility to you just got a lot harder."

        He grinned from ear to ear, then noticed the ribbon.  Turning to
Tnai, he asked, "Where is the ribbon I brought?"

        Tnai motioned to the one I wore in my hair.  His eyes narrowed.

        "It was a pink one," he said accusingly to Tnai.  Tnai smiled
and nodded.

"And when you held it, it was red. And for me green.  On Delight, it
turned blue," she grinned at the expression on his face, then glanced
down at the sack he held in his hand.  She sniffed at the air, and I
suddenly noticed the rich smell of hot fo
od.  My stomach rumbled.

        Tnai giggled.

        "That smells good," she declared.  Davon looked down at his sack
and grinned.

        "Almost forgot," he said.
Opening the sack he pulled out packages that steamed and wafted
wonderful smells into the air.  Tnai began opening them eagerly,
revealing meat rolls and fresh bread, fried pasties and fresh cookies.
Davon watched her happily, grinning like a fool.
  She looked up and caatching her.  His face flushed crimson.  She
chuckled, and her cheeks pinked very slightly.

        "Don't just stand around," she said firmly.  "Make yourself
useful.  Get rid of that."
She gestured at the tub.  I didn't think it was possible, but his face
blushed even deeper and he ducked his head away and tugged at the tub.
Tnai continued unwrapping packages.  When she got to the last one, she
gave a little yelp of surprise.

        "Ice cream!  Davon, all this..."  She raised an eyebrow.

        He nodded.

        "It was a good day, Tnai.  Some fool threw away four excellent
swords.  They fetched a pretty price."  He hefted the tub over the stone
threshold at the door, stopped and motioned to the food.  "Dig in, I'll
be right back."

        The door closed behind him.  Tnai stared after him, her face
unreadable.
She pushed her red hair back off her forehead, shook her head slightly
and smiled.

        "Come on, Delight," she said.  "Let's see if we can finish it
all off before Davon gets back."

        I burst out laughing, picturing Davon's face were he to return
and find all the food finished, with just the remains of the meal on the
floor between Tnai and me.  Tnai looked at me approvingly.

"Laughter suits you, Delight," she said.  I could hear Davon's whistle
approaching the door.    Tnai picked up a meat roll and motioned to me
to do the same as Davon entered, still grinning from ear to ear.  I slid
to the floor and leaned my back ag
nst the bed.  Davon sat next to me, grabbed a fruit pastie and began
devouring it.  He looked across the wonderful spread at Tnai.  His eyes
took in every detail of her appearance.   He smiled.

        "I must be dining with the two most beautiful ladies in the City
of Fayd tonight!" he exclaimed.  For the first time, Tnai seemed at a
loss for words.  While the two stared into each others' eyes, I snuck
another vegetable roll.

The good food, the warmth and all the events of the day began to take
their toll.  My eyelids drooped, and Tnai and Davon's conversation was a
pleasant background blur.  Davon talked on and on about great adventures
happening all around him, about h
is wish to join with others who were mounting a campaign to go out
beyond the Teeth of Shartan.
Somewhere in my drowsiness, I understood the sacrifice he made for me
and tried to open my eyes and tell him I could take care of Delight, but
heard the words in Tnai's voice instead of my own.  The thread of the
conversation slipped away from me tho
ugh I tried to fight sleep.  Tnai chuckled and murmured ".... the bed"
and I felt Davon's strong, familiar hands lift me and put me on the soft
mattress.  Smaller, softer hands brushed the hair back from my face, and
tucked the fur around my chin.

 I tried to protest that I wasn't sleepy at all, but I was just too
comfortable.  Their conversation buzzed around me as I fell asleep,
warm, clean, well-fed and feeling at home for perhaps the first time in
my life.

[N]ext message, (r)eply, (q)uoted reply, e(x)it:

Subject: Crafters' Who's Who
Board:   mpg.legends.crafter
Message: 7
From:    Bloodstar [Jedico]
Date:    09/04/96 at 13:17:00 EST

Greetings one and all,

     I would hope that all of you know me by now, at least well enough
to say 'Hi' or wake me when I fall asleep. But for those who haven't
been bored to death already by my life story, here it is in somewhat
condensed form.

     Many years ago, in my home deep in the Teeth of Shartan, I was...
An Duien A'Chlaidheimh. In the old tongue of my clan this means a man
of the sword. With others I defended both village and temple for much
of my life. This ended for me the day I lost my wife and only son on
the battlefield and was unable to save them. That night by their pyre,
I put down my blade forever and left my mountain home to roam wherever
my feet would take me.

     For years I wandered alone through the Teeth and down into the
desolate lands around the foothills of the Shartans. With my old
knowledge of weaponry I was able to scrape a living together repairing
damaged weapons and sharpening blades. I would often help out local
smiths with their extra work....and learned much from them as I did.

     Eventually my path wound by odd routes to the gates of Fayd. Here
I found at least a place where I could hope to rebuild a life and
perhaps learn more than just the basics of the weaponsmiths trade.
I had no more thought for tomorrow than that; a job to occupy my time
and a place to stay while I existed. There was not much I could call
a real life.

     Then I found Amilor, and discovered Him to be the same One I had
served so long ago, but known by a different name. In the Teeth we
knew not the ocean depths, but we knew the heights where eagles flew.
One part of me began to show a spark of life again and I knew I had
found a home and family in Amilor's temple.

     If you do not know who awakened the rest of my soul to life, then
I must not be shouting it loudly enough.  I never thought to love again
or that romance could find any soil to grow in the arid land of my
soul....until I met Lisanne. She has rekindled a flame in my heart
and started me living again. Damn but it's good to be alive!

               Even a weapon can be a work of art,
                        Jedico Bloodstar

