This is THE place for rules information regarding crafting. It will contain
all of the restrictions and advantages gained upon reaching mastery as well
as general rules information. It is a read-only topic. -Morthain

Subject: Crafting - OOC Rules
Board:   mpg.legends.crafter
Message: 1
From:    KKlunk [Morthain Da'Karian]
Date:    09/03/96 at 18:24:02 EST

Well, if you are reading this, then you probably belong here. This is
the first in what will probably be a LONG list of posts covering the
rules around crafting. Here is the first rule, rankings:

Rank  1 -  6 : Novice
Rank  7 - 12 : Apprentice
Rank 13 - 19 : Journeyman    [Note: These two names are NOT sexist
Rank 20 - 29 : Craftsman     in any way, it is just the terms used]
Rank 30 +    : Master

And here is what you get for each ranking:

Novice     : You get laughed at by your fellows alot, but that's it.
Apprentice : You get to laugh at the novices. (Well, it's  start!)
Journeyman : You are considered a serious craftsperson, you can get
             access to the message boards now and laugh at your fellows.
Craftsman  : You are an expert in your craft, you begin to accrue
             special orders (see section below.)
Master     : You get to laugh at everybody, aren't you glad your here?
             You continue to accrue special orders (see below.)

Special Orders - Here are the basic rules:
You get your FIRST special order at rank 20 in all crafts.

              +1/4 weeks for each full 10 ranks above 30.
Woodlore    : 1/2 weeks at rank 20, 2/2 at 25, 3/2 at 30.
              +1/2 weeks for each full 10 ranks above 30.
Dyer/Weaver : 1/2 weeks at rank 20, 2/2 at 25, 3/2 at 30.
              +1/2 weeks for each full 10 ranks above 30.
                            (notice a pattern?)
Jeweler     : 1/2 weeks at rank 20, 2/2 at 25,
              +1/2 weeks for each full 10 ranks above 30.
                       (your quick! I'm sarcastic!)
Alchemy     : 1 free component (any)/2 weeks, 2/2 a

Notes : Only the four skills listed above are affected by or ranked by
        the previous rulings. Mining & ALchemy will be covered later
        after I have had a chance to talk things over with people.

OK, on to the next post: Rules for Specials

-Morthain Da'Karian

[N]ext message, (r)eply, (q)uoted reply, e(x)it:

Subject: Crafting - OOC Rules
Board:   mpg.legends.crafter
Message: 2
From:    KKlunk [Morthain Da'Karian]
Date:    09/03/96 at 18:43:24 EST

Rules for Specials :

1> Each item must already have a counterpart in the system, if you don't
   know, please REPORT up and ask.

2> Each item NAME may be preceded by up to 3 adjectives. Again, these
   adjectives must already exist.

3> Each item NAME can be followed by a string of up to 79 characters
   following it. The space following the name is automatic and not part
   of the 79 characters you are allowed.

4> Each item can have a LOOK or READ description. This description is
   limited to approximately 240 characters (3 lines) in length. It can
   be pretty much anything, so have fun with it. A common use is to put
   your own 'signature' on a piece. As an example, Durnik now places a
   stylized 'D' on all weapons he crafts as specials.

That was the easy part, now the hard part, paying for it:

You must give me ALL materials used in making the item with the
following exceptions:

 Leather, Steel, Cotton

I require all the dyes and other materials needed to make the item,
otherwise you will have to pay a fee for the materials, which I will
make sure are more than astronomical enough to make you wish you had the
materials <grin>. And YES this means you can't make a silk shirt in the
dead of winter unless you bought silk during the warm months!!!

Now, to offset this evil nasty plot to make you all carry 400 pounds of
stuff I will allow you to turn materials into me IN ADVANCE. I will
track the amount of material and subtract it as you use it. Please note:
this is a ONE-WAY process. Once I have it, there is no getting it back.
PERIOD, there will be NO exceptions! So don't give me that rainbow
diamond to hold unless you are SURE you will use it, as the instant I
record it I will be erasing it from the system (efficient, ain't I?)

I will accept dyes, metals, gems, and cloth. I will NOT accept animal
parts or completed items for storage, they are your responsibility.

Now, there is an advantage to this system I will cover under the next
post about materials.

-Morthain Da'Karian

[N]ext message, (r)eply, (q)uoted reply, e(x)it:

Subject: Crafting - OOC Rules
Board:   mpg.legends.crafter
Message: 3
From:    KKlunk [Morthain Da'Karian]
Date:    09/03/96 at 19:19:22 EST

Materials & their uses.

If you want a really nice big gem in an item you craft, don't give it to
me, I promise I will forget it. Give me gems only to get them out of
your inventory for use as small pieces. Basically all gems of normal
size and clarity can be used for a single center-piece or 4 minor pieces
(as in the smaller gems in a ring around the center stone). Please note
the following limits:

1> I will only hold Diamonds, Emeralds, Rubies, Sapphires, Pearls, and
   Opals (this includes the various types)

2> Each gem has a base value of 2 modified as follows:

   Tiny (-1)    Small (-0.5)   Large (+2)   Huge (+4)

   Damaged (-1.5)   Chipped (-1)   Polished (+1)   Faceted (+2)
   Brilliant (+3)   Flawless (+4)

I will be tracking these on a pure value basis for your items. As I
said, you want a huge gem in a ring, don't give it to me until I deliver
the ring!!!


Now, onto another topic, metals & jeweling. Some items are smaller than
others. 1 piece of metal can be used to do the following tasks:

Produce 2 pieces of jewelry (see exceptions below).
Be spun into a spool of thread good for 5 pieces of clothing.
Produce 1 of the following:
  A weapon (any type)
  A plate, pocketwatch, watch, scepter, rod, or wand.

(Please note, if you want the wand to have charges or the weapon to have
bonuses, craft it yourself and hand it to me when I deliver your order!)


And this final topic, at least for tonight. Jeweling (as it affects
peoples specials):

If you want a gem in a special you need to either:

 A> Be a jeweler of rank 5 or higher.
 B> Be prepared to pay me a flat 250 gold per item.


Now, since that takes away from weaver's and smith's a bit, here is
something you get back:

Weaving:

When making a special for an 'event', say a wedding, a ball, etc. the
entire OUTFIT is considered ONE special order. (Yes, this means
EVERYTHING worn by a single person. The items MUST all match, and be
gaudy enough to be used for nothing else, otherwise they will be treated
seperately!!!)

Wedding rings are also to be considered a SINGLE order for the pair.

Weaponsmiths, you now have the ability to repair broken weapons. I will
post the information later, but the end result is you can repair them
and also meld weapons together to produce a slightly better weapon. I
will be talking with you individually to get your feedback on these new
rules before I implement them any further than they are now in use.


-Morthain {I need my finger tips vulcanized} Da'Karian

