Message: 2
From:    Rablrousr [Delight]
Date:    09/06/96 at 19:06:34 EST

ho, boy, ho boy... *grins*
ideas, huh?  I've been crafting as a master for over a year now, and boy
have I come up with some ideas for you.. some I've been told are
downright impossible, some unlikely, and some just never really got
worked on... I'll try to categorize a bit...

Events: how about a chance for crafters to head out to faraway places to
try to find new methods of working? Or to obtain rare metals, dyes,
fabrics, etc.. (I hear there's a place called NuYawk or something ike
that where denim is just lying around!)
Obviously, the usual standbys... auctions, special crafter's nights,
etc.
also, sometime last year the Foresters sponsored a night for estblished
citizens to get rid of some of their accumulated possessions by donating
them to a pile for newer citizens to pick through... you could put a
limit on it (level and/or item) or make it an all out swap meet..


Okay, here's  a few of the things I'd like to see added...

1) Like it or not, weaving is tiring work. Why shouldn't we see some
fatigue?
 In real life, you can't work non stop without getting overtired.

2) Random failures -- especially as you get fatigued, it's easy to sew a
sleeve in backwards, stitch a seam crooked and have to rip it out, etc.
Like
in any other skill, the failures should be more frequent at lower levels
and
decrease as skill grows. ... it could be done similar to the way cotton
or wool is
worked... a failure requires another step in the weaving process.

3)New skills at new levels... some suggestions --
a)embroidery -- like engraving in jeweler, only instead of saying
'engraved
with the writing' it would say 'embroidered with' and give the crafter
sixty
characters of description to add to the item... say at level 40 or 45.

b) weaving with metal -- at say, level 50, the ability to spin thread
from
pure metals, and weave with them. And assign small dmod factors to the
various metals. Say a cloak woven of pure silver thread adds 1 point of
dmod,
elkyri metal 2, etc.

c) Getting a bit more complicated, a weaver with some alchemy skill, or
a
high level weaver shoudl be able to combine dye items to come up with
new
colors....


d) After level 75, say, a weaver might be able to call on a god once
every
five levels to add a special 'blessing' to an item of clothing --  maybe
it
can cast night vision, say.. (there's a bodysuit scripted that does
exactly
that.) Or 7 league boots, that allow the wearer to return to BC from
wherever
they are (with limited charges, of course.)

These are things that would encourage players to advance in weaving.
Right
now, beyond level 30, there's no reason to do that. I know at least one
character who had over 100 builds saved up, because there was nothing
else to
spend them on... all she wanted was to be a weaver. She learned enough
psi to
have contact, and everything else was in weaving.

Other things that would make crafting a viable option for advancement...
Quarterly auctions like the one that Hyena planned and held in November.

Actually, any kind of market that makes buying woven goods more
attractive to
the regular player.

A real guild, as opposed to a building where people congregate loosely
to
hang out scripted and weave. Hyena and I did a lot of talking about this
before he went on hiatus... Among the things we discussed were things
that
had to do with other crafts -- like actually paying for dye items. Right
now,
it's barely worth it to forage, since most foragers give away anything
that
doesn't command high prices (stat herbs, for instance.) Get more of the
guilds to incorporate special colors, like the Crimson Band does --- the
worth of the dye item that makes that color will increase dramatically,
making it more worthwhile to find it. Some events targeted for weavers
--
say, an expedition to get a cache of valuable fabrics (velvet and denim
should be almost impossible to get) or a journey to consult with a
master
weaver to learn how to combine dyes for different effects -- stripes,
tie
dye (a pink polka dot dye is ridiculous, for instance! But it exists.)


Well, this is a whole lot longer than I planned on, but it does hit most
of
what I've been thinking...

sorry you asked?
De

[N]ext message, (r)eply, (q)uoted reply, e(x)it:

Subject: Ideas & Things
Board:   mpg.legends.crafter
Message: 3
From:    Stardemon
Date:    09/06/96 at 20:35:36 EST

     Hello,
     First let me introduce myself for those of you who don't know me.
I am Raningeth Ironheart, a simple Gnome, Temple of Amilor's Alchemist
and minor Priest.  I can Craft all known potions and have a few ideas.
Many I have passed on to Morthain.
     I would like to see alchemy expanded.  I think as an alchemist I
should be able to mix metals with the possibility of creating new
alloys.  Maybe they could be stronger, hotter or simple a new metal.  I
think we should be able say mix a metal and imbed it with a potion to
form a magical weapon.  For example, I smelt soem elkeri and add some
iron, before it cools I add in the entire contents of one bottle of
Strength III potion.  Once cooled I take the ore and find a master smith
and he crafts a dagger or sword with it.  The next logical step would be
to find a master enchanter and have him cast enchant weapon on it.  If
every thing goes well (every step should have a chance of failure which
is not know till the weapon is crafted).  The weapon if completed and
successful would have the magical plus of the crafted elkeri dagger and
slightly better strength then steel and have 10 charges of strength III.
This would be a cool way to craft new weapons.  Maybe a couple of added
alchemical processess and a few more spells and the weapon could
regenerate its charges ever 24 hours.  That would be a cool think for an
alchemist to be able to do.
     I think the same this could apply to forming other magical items.
Here is an example:  Delight wants to make a cloak of mist Form.  Its
determined that she needs harpie hairs soaked in a compound of myst
potion and mind link.  Why soaking an enchanter must cast enchant item
of the whole mixture.  Then Delight would have to spin the hairs into
thread to make a special cloth.  This cloth then might have to have mist
form cast upon it enchant item once again.  Once this was accomplised
she might then make the cloak.  When finished it might have a number of
charges that allow the cloak when pulled to allow the wearer to mist
form.  Maybe when soaking I made 50 sips of the particular potion and
the threads absorbed about 35 or so and so the finished cloak might have
35 charges.
     I think alchemist should also be able to make vials, bottles and
flasks from glass.  Maybe by finding the ingredients for glass and then
brewing them like a potion. Lets say at level 30 Alchemist gain blow
glass skill.  and you add verb blow, (blow glass vial).  Raningeth
Ironheart takes a pieces of moten class and forms a flask out of it.
     Of course we need new potions, ones that don't have a sister spell,
then us alchemist could really make a buck.  I look at an alchemist as a
tinker.  I wonder what would happen if I took a few acorns and soaked
them in strength potion and had and enchanter cast enchant item on them.
     Well I have rambled on for long enough.
     Raningeth Ironheart

